ential audience, and for international fame. The story of Mark Twain’s life and art, amid this media revolution, is a story with powerful implications for our own time, as we ride another wave of radical change: for printed texts, authors, truth, and consciousness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAuthors and publisherszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPrinting in literature. 0aPrintingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPublishers and publishingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aamerican publishing history.  aamericana.  aconsequences of a revolution.  acultural revolution.  aeasy to read.  aediting and publishing.  aengaging.  aepistemological.  aepistemology.  afamous american writers.  ahistorical.  ahistory of publishing.  ainternational fame.  alife changes.  alifetime.  alively.  amedia revolution.  ametaphysical power.  aprinting press.  apublishing and printing industry.  aradical change.  aretrospective.  atypesetting.  awood cutting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093284540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932845423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520932845/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles